The school might also gain from the government subsidy called 'feed-in-tariff'.

<p>The amount of the feed in tariff will depend on when the panels were installed and is typically in the range 5p/kWh to 40 p/kWh x the total 'Photovoltaic production' of 5,694 kWh, each year</p>

<p>There will be an extra saving of about £79 from exported electricity under the SEG (Smart Export Guarantee)</p>

<strong>If the panels are owned by a third-party</strong>

<p>Third party companies install solar panels for free and charge schools a discounted rate for the energy consumed from these panels.</p>

<p>So the savings will depend on the difference between the cost of mains electricity and how much the third party is charging for electricity.</p>
